# Status & list-field consistency

## General principle (any list, any doc)

Field tracking in a list must be **exhaustive and uniform**. Once *any* item in a
list carries a field (a status, an owner, a severity, a checkbox), **every** item
in that list — including ones you add later — must carry the same field. Never
leave a mixed list where some items are annotated and others are not. If you add a
new item to an annotated list, annotate it; if you start annotating, backfill the
existing items.

## ROADMAP.md: one status, recorded in four places

`docs/ROADMAP.md` records each item's status in places that must always agree:

1. the **Checklist** table — the `Status` column;
2. the item's section header — the `**Status**:` line under `### R-xx.`;
3. inline mentions — `~~R-xx~~ (status)` strikethroughs (strikethrough ⇒ `done`/`rejected`);
4. `CHANGELOG.md` — `(Roadmap R-xx, …)` references imply the item shipped (`done`/`in-progress`).

When you change one item's status, update **all** of these. When you add an item,
add it to both the table and a section with a matching status. Allowed statuses:
`needs-decision`, `accepted`, `in-progress`, `done`, `rejected`.

## Verify mechanically — don't eyeball it

After editing `docs/ROADMAP.md` or `CHANGELOG.md`, run the checker instead of
manually scanning for missed spots:

```bash
python scripts/check_roadmap.py
```

It must print "consistent" (exit 0). The same check runs in CI
(`tests/test_roadmap_consistency.py`) and via a `stop` hook, so unresolved drift
will block you later — fix it now.
